Step 0 - Create Question3 folder. 
cd ~/Linux-Lab-Assignment
mkdir Question2
cd Question2

pwd

Step 1 - 
touch commands.txt output.txt explanation.txt
ls

Part 1 - 
Commands - 
echo "This is sample data for link testing" > ~/sample_data.txt

Output - 
(no output)

Explanation - 
This command creates the file sample_data.txt in the home directory and writes sample text into it.

Part 2 - 
Commands - 
ln ~/sample_data.txt ~/sample_hard.txt

Output - 
(No output)

Explanation -
The ln command creates a hard link that points to the same inode as the original file.

Part 3 - 
Commands - 
ln -s ~/sample_data.txt ~/sample_soft.txt

Output - 
(No output) 

Explanation -
The ln -s command creates a symbolic link that references the original file path.

Part 4 - 
Commands - 
ls -i ~/sample_data.txt ~/sample_hard.txt ~/sample_soft.txt

Output - 
233344 sample_data.txt
233344 sample_hard.txt
229437 sample_soft.txt

Explanation -
ls -i displays inode numbers for files.

Part 5 - 
Commands - 
No commands.

Explanation -
sample_data.txt and sample_hard.txt share the same inode number because a hard link points to the same physical file on disk.
The symbolic link has a different inode because it only stores the path to the original file.

Part 6 - 
Commands - 
ls -l ~/sample_data.txt

Output - 
- rw - r - - r - - 2 coder coder 37 Jan 4 16:29 /home/coder/sample_data.txt
Explanation -
ls -l displays permissions, ownership, size, and timestamp details of the file.

Part 7 - 
Commands - 
du -sh ~

Output - 
38M    /home/coder

Explanation -
du -sh shows the total disk usage of the home directory in a human-readable format.

Part 8 - 
Commands - 
ls -lh ~

Output - 
screenshot

Explanation -
ls -lh lists files with their sizes displayed in a human-readable format.

Part 9 - 
Commands - 
rm ~/sample_soft.txt
cat ~/sample_data.txt

Output - 
screenshot

Explanation -
Removing the symbolic link does not affect the original file.
The original file contents remain intact.

Part 10- 
Commands - 
du -h ~
df -h

Output - 
screenshot

Explanation -
du -h displays disk usage of files and directories.
df -h shows filesystem disk space usage including total, used, and available space.

